title: For Sale/Trade:  Custom Built 1911
postcontent:
So when I say custom built, I don't mean that in the "custom AR build" sense where you put an Aero Precision upper on a PSA lower and sell it for double their combined retail values. Built off of a Remington frame but that and the barrel are the only Remington parts in it.

All internals are a perfectly blended gluten free smoothie of STI, Les Baer, Ed Brown, Caspian, and Wilson Combat. Sourcing only the best parts for the pinnacle of design meets function, all parts were dutifully hand fitted to eliminate any drag or grit whatsoever. Trigger pull is 3lbs and with limited pre travel and over travel, but it is still a series 80 so you do have that brief staging for the firing pin block safety.

All milling and Cerakote work was done aftermarket and the slide is a one of a kind design with the radius being converted to 5 trued flats, aesthetic and lightening notches on the top, window cuts, and a recess on either side for contrast highlighted with Cerakote. Rear Novak sight cut and a set of brand new bright Trijicon night sights. Extractor/ejector blended to slide/frame.

Comes with 2 8 round mags and hard case. Can meet locally, drive to meet within 2 hours of Denver, or ship to your FFL

$1800 approximate trade value, have a bottom line in mind but open to offers, trades or trade plus cash always welcome

title: Want To Buy:  Saiga-12 Gas Port Adjustment Work
postcontent:
I have an older Saiga-12 that won't reliably cycle the low brass "walmart" bulk ammo.  It will have 1 or 2 fail to eject and/or feeds per mag.  Those that do eject only go about 8" or so out.  I have had the bolt, carrier, and hammer all radiused and polished, as well as a low power recoil spring and 3-position aftermarket gas plug.  All of it helped, but none fixed it completely.


From what I have read there is a very good chance that the factory gas ports are undersized and/or the gas block is blocking some of them.  It seems straight forward enough to remove the block and drill the ports and what not, but at the same time I would rather have someone that has done it before look at it, since any screw up would be pretty tough to fix.

Any suggestions on where to take it locally, or at least on this side of the mountain?  Thanks!

title: For Sale:  Colt 1903 Pocket Hammerless - .32acp
location: White Bear Lake, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
This is a working man’s Colt 1903 Pocket Hammerless. Serial number is 330642. It was manufactured in 1920. 

It was the first 1903 I purchased. I got this firearm because I wanted to better understand the 1903/1908 Hammerless Colts.  This is a gun I carried on occasion, shot often, and let friends shoot it without worrying about messing up the finish. This is a good 1903 to have if it’s your first or if you have a couple of them safely tucked away this is one you’ll want to enjoy at the range.

I judge this pistol to be in good shape for being 95 years old. The slide and receiver have matching serial numbers. There is no rust or pitting on this firearm. The left side has a pronounced retention holster scratches above the trigger. The right side has minor scuff marks above and to the right of the grip. The pictures show these wear marks well. They are less noticeable in person. The slide has a dent in it on the right side above and ahead of the ejection port. It looks like someone before me touched up the dented area. They did a good job, as I just noticed it when I was photographing the firearm for this listing. Grips are in great shape with no chips or cracks. Barrel has strong rifling. The magazine is the original two tone. For me the firearm feed ammo well and shot well. 

The pictures show the condition of this gun.  For me, this firearm function properly but as with any curious & relic have it checked out by a gunsmith before taking that first shot.

Additional photos: https://www.flickr.com/photos/jnclarke/sets/REDACTED6684758/

title: For Sale:  Colt 1908 Vest Pocket - .25acp EXCELLENT
location: White Bear Lake, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
This is a beautiful Colt 1908 Vest Pocket. Serial number is 404264. It was manufactured in 1937. 

This pistol is in excellent condition. The slide and receiver have matching serial numbers. There is no rust or pitting on this firearm. You will see some sock drawer wear on the left side of the slide. It is more pronounced in the photo than it is in your hand. The grips are in excellent condition with sharp checkering. Note the back half of the right grip. This seems to be a manufacturing defect. I guess times were tough in 1937. The barrel and rifling are in outstanding condition with sharp pronounced grooves and lands. This firearm has the original 2 tone magazine that is in great condition. I have shot this firearm but not often. It was just too good looking to be taking it to the range. It functioned flawlessly for me.

The pictures show the condition of this gun.  For me, this firearm function properly but, as with any curious & relic, have it checked out by a gunsmith before taking that first shot.

title: For Sale:  Martian Commercial - .25acp
location: White Bear Lake, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
This is a "Martian Commercial".  Made by Martin A. Bascaran in Eibar, Spain from 1919 until about 1928. 

It is pretty much a knockoff of the 1906 Browning/1908 Colt Vest Pocket. Serial number is 13187. A number matching specimen as Barrel, Frame, and Slide have a 107 assembly number. This pistol is in good shape with no pitting or rust. Grips are in great shape with no chips or cracks. Barrel has strong rifling. 

If you want a reliable, safe to carry shooter buy a Browning or a Colt. If you want an example of Spain’s total disregard of Browning’s brilliance consider this pistol. The pictures show the condition of this gun.  This firearm appears to function properly but as with any curious & relic have it checked out by a gunsmith before taking that first shot.
